00:00:21.602 --> 00:00:23.060
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
So just as kind

00:00:23.060 --> 00:00:26.600
of a synopsis of
some ideas that we're

00:00:26.600 --> 00:00:29.990
going to get through, we're
looking at manufacturing, which

00:00:29.990 --> 00:00:31.770
is a way to profit
from innovation,

00:00:31.770 --> 00:00:34.340
as a way to scale innovation.

00:00:34.340 --> 00:00:37.250
And we'll do something of an
historical review here today,

00:00:37.250 --> 00:00:41.390
so we'll look at the last big
competitiveness challenge.

00:00:41.390 --> 00:00:44.920
The US went through a challenge
from Germany and Japan.

00:00:44.920 --> 00:00:47.510
We'll take a particular look
at Japan's manufacturing

00:00:47.510 --> 00:00:50.660
innovations in the '70s.

00:00:50.660 --> 00:00:54.350
We'll review a distributed
model of production

00:00:54.350 --> 00:00:59.110
that the US came up with,
in some ways in response.

00:00:59.110 --> 00:01:01.340
We'll look at manufacturing
and innovation

00:01:01.340 --> 00:01:06.230
organizational shifts
within both Korea and Japan,

00:01:06.230 --> 00:01:08.840
and then talk a bit about how
the nature of the competition

00:01:08.840 --> 00:01:12.210
is changing as well.

00:01:12.210 --> 00:01:14.660
So that's kind of a
backdrop, and then next week

00:01:14.660 --> 00:01:17.260
will be a more pointed focus.

00:01:17.260 --> 00:01:20.270
So the first piece we'll go
through, and I'll lay it out.

00:01:20.270 --> 00:01:23.770
And Chris, do you have--

00:01:23.770 --> 00:01:25.080
RASHEED, you've got Hughes.

00:01:25.080 --> 00:01:25.663
RASHEED: Yeah.

00:01:25.663 --> 00:01:26.990
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Right, OK.

00:01:26.990 --> 00:01:29.160
So this is Kent Hughes.

00:01:29.160 --> 00:01:38.870
Kent Huges led the joint
economic committee,

00:01:38.870 --> 00:01:40.550
staff director in the Congress.

00:01:40.550 --> 00:01:42.965
He was a senior official in
the Department of Commerce.

00:01:42.965 --> 00:01:47.180
And he kind of wrote the
history of the competition

00:01:47.180 --> 00:01:53.180
over production between US
and China, a period of time

00:01:53.180 --> 00:01:57.960
when he was very deeply
engaged in policy making.

00:01:57.960 --> 00:02:00.530
So let's get this
backdrop kind of down

00:02:00.530 --> 00:02:02.000
because I think
it'll help us see

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:05.630
a lot about what the US is
going through now in terms

00:02:05.630 --> 00:02:07.580
of manufacturing.

00:02:07.580 --> 00:02:14.530
So in the 1970s, the
US faced a mess--

00:02:14.530 --> 00:02:20.860
intractable high inflation,
declining productivity growth,

00:02:20.860 --> 00:02:25.750
therefore a slow growth rate,
rising economic competition,

00:02:25.750 --> 00:02:29.710
rising national anger,
frustration with government.

00:02:29.710 --> 00:02:32.140
Sound familiar?

00:02:32.140 --> 00:02:35.470
And the US model of kind of
pretty unfettered markets

00:02:35.470 --> 00:02:38.500
of limited government
support for industry

00:02:38.500 --> 00:02:40.690
was a very different
innovation model,

00:02:40.690 --> 00:02:43.300
innovation system than
what Japan and Germany were

00:02:43.300 --> 00:02:45.640
pursuing.

00:02:45.640 --> 00:02:49.163
And that in turn led
to the beginnings

00:02:49.163 --> 00:02:51.455
of what could be called the
US National Competitiveness

00:02:51.455 --> 00:02:54.185
Strategy.

00:02:54.185 --> 00:03:00.250
So the essential
elements of that history

00:03:00.250 --> 00:03:03.590
of the initial response to
Japan's development of quality

00:03:03.590 --> 00:03:07.040
manufacturing, which we'll
get into in a minute,

00:03:07.040 --> 00:03:10.640
there were different
responses from each party.

00:03:10.640 --> 00:03:13.260
And these will be
familiar to you as well.

00:03:13.260 --> 00:03:17.260
So each party was organized--

00:03:17.260 --> 00:03:19.970
remember when we discussed
classical economics, right?

00:03:19.970 --> 00:03:21.840
And the key factors
in classical economics

00:03:21.840 --> 00:03:24.380
were capital supply
and labor supply.

00:03:24.380 --> 00:03:28.310
Each of our parties is organized
around one of these, right?

00:03:28.310 --> 00:03:36.070
So the capital supply response
came from the Republican side,

00:03:36.070 --> 00:03:41.572
and Congressman Jack Kemp
of Buffalo and Bill Roth,

00:03:41.572 --> 00:03:43.280
who was chairman of
the Finance Committee

00:03:43.280 --> 00:03:47.420
and the Senate from
Delaware, their argument was,

00:03:47.420 --> 00:03:50.470
let's adjust marginal
tax rates that

00:03:50.470 --> 00:03:54.050
will spur capital
availability and investment.

00:03:54.050 --> 00:03:55.620
And we'll recover.

00:03:55.620 --> 00:03:58.520
The Democrats will
organize around

00:03:58.520 --> 00:04:00.650
their traditional
mantra of labor supply,

00:04:00.650 --> 00:04:03.830
broadly defined, right?

00:04:03.830 --> 00:04:07.160
And they had moved
towards what was then

00:04:07.160 --> 00:04:09.140
known as industrial
policy, still known

00:04:09.140 --> 00:04:11.160
as industrial policy.

00:04:11.160 --> 00:04:17.329
So they were looking to
rescuing failing industries

00:04:17.329 --> 00:04:20.870
and reorganizing
them for turnarounds.

00:04:20.870 --> 00:04:26.920
And at a later time, through
the Young Commission,

00:04:26.920 --> 00:04:31.120
another set of ideas begins to
enter the discussion around,

00:04:31.120 --> 00:04:34.300
quote, sunrise industries.

00:04:34.300 --> 00:04:37.840
The Young Commission tired to
cut between these two party

00:04:37.840 --> 00:04:41.660
perspectives and develop
a different approach.

00:04:41.660 --> 00:04:44.980
So John Young was head
of Hewlett Packard,

00:04:44.980 --> 00:04:48.280
and President Reagan named him
the head of this commission.

00:04:48.280 --> 00:04:52.450
And their focus was on
national competitiveness.

00:04:52.450 --> 00:04:56.250
And they concurred that things
like fiscal and monetary policy

00:04:56.250 --> 00:04:58.540
are important.

00:04:58.540 --> 00:05:01.890
But they were also interested
in what the innovation side

00:05:01.890 --> 00:05:03.740
of the research side could do.

00:05:03.740 --> 00:05:05.860
So it was not simply
a governmental role

00:05:05.860 --> 00:05:09.322
in basic research,
but basic technology.

00:05:09.322 --> 00:05:10.780
And they developed
a model that was

00:05:10.780 --> 00:05:13.750
in this public private
partnership that

00:05:13.750 --> 00:05:16.150
was industry led.

00:05:16.150 --> 00:05:19.240
And the term partnership
nation emerged

00:05:19.240 --> 00:05:20.920
from some of their work.

00:05:20.920 --> 00:05:24.770
So this was, in effect, a
third way out of the box.

00:05:24.770 --> 00:05:27.670
The two parties had their
underlying theories.

00:05:27.670 --> 00:05:30.610
And Young walks in with a
different kind of approach.

00:05:30.610 --> 00:05:33.130
So he's out of the
Silicon Valley.

00:05:33.130 --> 00:05:35.920
He's used to working with DARPA
and the Defense Department,

00:05:35.920 --> 00:05:40.050
so he's not afraid of government
and its technology support

00:05:40.050 --> 00:05:41.140
rule.

00:05:41.140 --> 00:05:47.590
And this whole effort
was called the New Growth

00:05:47.590 --> 00:05:49.930
Compact, all right?

00:05:49.930 --> 00:05:54.190
So it was an attempt to
cut between the parties

00:05:54.190 --> 00:05:56.575
and develop a series of
new programmatic elements.

00:05:56.575 --> 00:05:58.990
So some of the things
that eventually emerged--

00:05:58.990 --> 00:06:01.540
not specifically from the
recommendations necessarily,

00:06:01.540 --> 00:06:03.660
but emerged over time--

00:06:03.660 --> 00:06:07.600
were created as
cooperative R&D agreements

00:06:07.600 --> 00:06:12.340
with industry between
governmental laboratories

00:06:12.340 --> 00:06:13.160
and industry.

00:06:13.160 --> 00:06:16.840
So in other words, we've got
these snappy governmental labs.

00:06:16.840 --> 00:06:18.410
Little emerges from them.

00:06:18.410 --> 00:06:20.560
Could we do
cooperative agreements

00:06:20.560 --> 00:06:22.450
to get technologies
out of the labs

00:06:22.450 --> 00:06:23.860
into the hands of industry?

00:06:23.860 --> 00:06:25.440
It's a new tool.

00:06:25.440 --> 00:06:29.480
The Bayh-Dole Act comes out
of the same time period,

00:06:29.480 --> 00:06:34.000
which, prior to the Bayh-Dole
Act, the federal government

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:37.330
owned the fruits of
the research that it

00:06:37.330 --> 00:06:39.520
supported at universities.

00:06:39.520 --> 00:06:41.770
Now the federal government
is not a commercial entity,

00:06:41.770 --> 00:06:44.800
so nothing happened to it.

00:06:44.800 --> 00:06:47.310
So it was moved
to shelves, right?

00:06:47.310 --> 00:06:50.520
The IP was not really utilized.

00:06:50.520 --> 00:06:55.140
So Bayh and Dole came up
with the idea of giving

00:06:55.140 --> 00:06:57.570
the universities that had
sponsored the research

00:06:57.570 --> 00:06:59.850
activities-- supported the
research activities with

00:06:59.850 --> 00:07:01.020
federal funds--

00:07:01.020 --> 00:07:02.450
let's give them ownership.

00:07:02.450 --> 00:07:06.060
And they in turn typically
share it with their researchers

00:07:06.060 --> 00:07:11.190
and give them a vested stake
in developing the technologies

00:07:11.190 --> 00:07:13.170
that the research is leading to.

00:07:13.170 --> 00:07:14.790
So this plays a
really critical role

00:07:14.790 --> 00:07:18.120
in starting to put universities
on the playing field

00:07:18.120 --> 00:07:19.795
as innovation actors, right?

00:07:19.795 --> 00:07:24.510
It gives them a stake in the
outcomes of their research.

00:07:24.510 --> 00:07:27.325
The Advanced Technology Program
and the Manufacturing Extension

00:07:27.325 --> 00:07:29.700
Program come out of the Commerce
Department in an attempt

00:07:29.700 --> 00:07:36.750
to introduce both new
technologies and an attempt

00:07:36.750 --> 00:07:40.230
in the MEP program
to bring advances

00:07:40.230 --> 00:07:43.020
Japan had been pushing
on quality production

00:07:43.020 --> 00:07:47.090
into small US manufacturers.

00:07:47.090 --> 00:07:50.070
There were education proposals.

00:07:50.070 --> 00:07:52.843
That attitude was
essentially pro-trade.

00:07:52.843 --> 00:07:55.110
In other words, don't
ignore the world.

00:07:55.110 --> 00:07:59.370
Let's be successful at trade
and be innovative in trade.

00:07:59.370 --> 00:08:02.480
That attitude gets adopted
by the Clinton administration

00:08:02.480 --> 00:08:07.200
and leads to things like
NAFTA and the China WTO.

00:08:07.200 --> 00:08:11.820
So that's kind of what is coming
out of the Young Commission

00:08:11.820 --> 00:08:14.383
in terms of new ideas, but
let's go back to the challenge

00:08:14.383 --> 00:08:15.300
that they were facing.

00:08:15.300 --> 00:08:16.860
What was this?

00:08:16.860 --> 00:08:21.110
What was this new
model around production

00:08:21.110 --> 00:08:23.460
that Japan was launching?

00:08:23.460 --> 00:08:28.650
And I would argue that
was big enough so that it,

00:08:28.650 --> 00:08:32.789
in fact, amounted to a
significant innovation wave.

00:08:32.789 --> 00:08:36.059
And it was the one
wave that the US

00:08:36.059 --> 00:08:40.690
missed in the second
half of the 20th century.

00:08:40.690 --> 00:08:47.280
So Japan hit on innovating
and manufacturing

00:08:47.280 --> 00:08:51.000
as a way towards its
own competitiveness

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:55.260
as a leading world
economic power.

00:08:55.260 --> 00:08:59.880
And before the 1970s,
the US had come up

00:08:59.880 --> 00:09:03.690
with a way of dealing with
quality in what's called

00:09:03.690 --> 00:09:06.980
a quality price tradeoff.

00:09:06.980 --> 00:09:09.180
So in our mass
production system--

00:09:09.180 --> 00:09:11.630
and the US essentially
came up with most

00:09:11.630 --> 00:09:13.400
of the elements
of mass production

00:09:13.400 --> 00:09:20.150
starting around the 1840s
and moving for 100 years.

00:09:20.150 --> 00:09:22.070
The US had become
a dominant mass

00:09:22.070 --> 00:09:25.490
produ-- we had really invented
mass production at huge scale.

00:09:25.490 --> 00:09:27.260
And we were selling
manufactured goods

00:09:27.260 --> 00:09:29.150
into a continent sized economy.

00:09:29.150 --> 00:09:31.490
Of course, continent sized
economy that existed.

00:09:35.080 --> 00:09:36.910
And part of the
mass production idea

00:09:36.910 --> 00:09:40.960
was never stop the
production line.

00:09:40.960 --> 00:09:42.100
Always keep it moving.

00:09:42.100 --> 00:09:44.500
Always keep producing.

00:09:44.500 --> 00:09:47.620
And how do you
deal with quality?

00:09:47.620 --> 00:09:49.720
Well, you do
statistical analysis

00:09:49.720 --> 00:09:52.330
of the products
you were producing.

00:09:52.330 --> 00:09:57.700
You would decide that some fixed
percentage were not meeting

00:09:57.700 --> 00:09:59.710
those quality standards.

00:09:59.710 --> 00:10:03.760
And so at the end of the
system, after you would produce

00:10:03.760 --> 00:10:07.120
the goods, you would have an
inspection group throw out

00:10:07.120 --> 00:10:08.170
whatever it was--

00:10:08.170 --> 00:10:14.020
1.8%, 2.4%, whatever the
statistical number told you--

00:10:14.020 --> 00:10:18.220
after the production
system had been developed.

00:10:18.220 --> 00:10:20.290
Quality is really how
good is the product.

00:10:20.290 --> 00:10:23.580
Quality control is
what's the unit of--

00:10:23.580 --> 00:10:25.450
are there units
of equal quality,

00:10:25.450 --> 00:10:28.600
right, across all
that you're producing?

00:10:28.600 --> 00:10:32.200
Japan came up with a
completely different system

00:10:32.200 --> 00:10:34.930
and a much better system.

00:10:34.930 --> 00:10:37.770
And it was called
here the Toyota model.

00:10:37.770 --> 00:10:40.640
But it was based in
Japanese manufacturing.

00:10:40.640 --> 00:10:45.010
So the idea here was build
quality into each product,

00:10:45.010 --> 00:10:48.400
not at the end of the system,
throw a bunch of stuff away.

00:10:48.400 --> 00:10:52.450
Ensure that the entire system
is working to ensure quality.

00:10:52.450 --> 00:10:56.050
And anyone, any worker, can
stop the production line

00:10:56.050 --> 00:10:57.850
if they see a quality problem.

00:10:57.850 --> 00:11:01.630
So catch it at the
beginning and build quality

00:11:01.630 --> 00:11:03.130
into your entire
production process.

00:11:05.840 --> 00:11:09.040
The idea came actually from an
American named Edward Deming.

00:11:09.040 --> 00:11:12.770
And he was unable to persuade
US manufacturers to adopt

00:11:12.770 --> 00:11:13.270
this model.

00:11:13.270 --> 00:11:16.390
So he takes it to Japan.

00:11:16.390 --> 00:11:21.190
And we sense
Japan's rich culture

00:11:21.190 --> 00:11:24.010
here around
craftsmanship, right?

00:11:24.010 --> 00:11:25.910
It fits wonderfully with it.

00:11:25.910 --> 00:11:29.210
All right, so this is--

00:11:29.210 --> 00:11:33.860
Japanese samurai culture, of
course, respects the samurai,

00:11:33.860 --> 00:11:36.890
but accords almost
equivalent respect

00:11:36.890 --> 00:11:41.900
to the sword maker, right, who
is almost equally as famous.

00:11:41.900 --> 00:11:47.360
So there's a huge focus on
high quality and craftsmanship

00:11:47.360 --> 00:11:48.200
in Japanese culture.

00:11:48.200 --> 00:11:51.740
So what Deming is saying
fits with the kind

00:11:51.740 --> 00:11:56.930
of culture of Japan.

00:11:56.930 --> 00:11:59.510
There are other pieces
that Japan comes up with--

00:11:59.510 --> 00:12:01.940
just in time inventory.

00:12:01.940 --> 00:12:07.160
In other words, a major
burden that manufacturers face

00:12:07.160 --> 00:12:10.070
is that they have to store
up a lot of inventory

00:12:10.070 --> 00:12:13.440
to have enough goods
available for the marketplace.

00:12:13.440 --> 00:12:16.550
But when you hit an
economic downturn,

00:12:16.550 --> 00:12:18.860
then you're stuck with
this massive inventory

00:12:18.860 --> 00:12:20.570
that you can't
get rid of, right?

00:12:20.570 --> 00:12:23.870
And it becomes a huge cost
burden on your system.

00:12:23.870 --> 00:12:27.890
Japan's idea was produce for
what the market is actually

00:12:27.890 --> 00:12:29.230
absorbing--

00:12:29.230 --> 00:12:33.860
in other words, produce just
in time to get it to market.

00:12:33.860 --> 00:12:35.600
So that calls for
a whole new level

00:12:35.600 --> 00:12:39.410
of efficiency and
communications really

00:12:39.410 --> 00:12:42.555
IT embedded in
earlier kind of ways

00:12:42.555 --> 00:12:44.180
throughout the whole
production system.

00:12:46.930 --> 00:12:50.990
And it significantly
reduced the exposure

00:12:50.990 --> 00:12:54.980
of significant manufacturers
to economic downturns.

00:12:58.670 --> 00:13:08.500
Japan integrated its dealers and
its suppliers into its system.

00:13:08.500 --> 00:13:10.840
So in the US,
major manufacturers

00:13:10.840 --> 00:13:13.942
would keep their suppliers at
arm's length and have them bid.

00:13:13.942 --> 00:13:15.650
And there was no
particular relationship.

00:13:15.650 --> 00:13:18.273
They were just looking for
the lowest price, right?

00:13:18.273 --> 00:13:19.690
Japan, the suppliers
were actually

00:13:19.690 --> 00:13:21.490
integrated into that system.

00:13:21.490 --> 00:13:25.870
And in turn, the dealers who
were just selling these goods

00:13:25.870 --> 00:13:30.760
were also integrated in, so
that you had much closer touch

00:13:30.760 --> 00:13:33.130
with what customers
actually needed and wanted,

00:13:33.130 --> 00:13:36.590
as well as what the
quality of the suppliers,

00:13:36.590 --> 00:13:39.640
what they were producing,
is going to be.

00:13:39.640 --> 00:13:42.360
Japan had a culture of
respecting the production

00:13:42.360 --> 00:13:44.200
moment.

00:13:44.200 --> 00:13:46.330
So they would move
their engineers

00:13:46.330 --> 00:13:50.980
onto the factory floor as
their first set of assignments.

00:13:50.980 --> 00:13:54.250
So if you look at, in contrast,
the US didn't do that.

00:13:54.250 --> 00:13:54.750
All right?

00:13:54.750 --> 00:13:58.150
So the engineering
profession was

00:13:58.150 --> 00:14:00.490
one in the 19th century
US that was trying

00:14:00.490 --> 00:14:04.900
to take a hold with those
other established professions--

00:14:04.900 --> 00:14:07.540
doctors, lawyers, ministers.

00:14:07.540 --> 00:14:10.570
So when you look at these
early photographs of MIT

00:14:10.570 --> 00:14:12.225
and you look at
photographs of MIT

00:14:12.225 --> 00:14:16.510
labs, those wonderful
photographs of the steam lab,

00:14:16.510 --> 00:14:20.356
you can't imagine coal
dust all over the place.

00:14:20.356 --> 00:14:21.731
These characters
were all wearing

00:14:21.731 --> 00:14:26.212
these starched white shirts
with those fancy weird bow

00:14:26.212 --> 00:14:28.420
ties they wore at the end
of the 19th century, right?

00:14:28.420 --> 00:14:30.160
They looked so prim and proper.

00:14:30.160 --> 00:14:33.090
They're trying to be like
ministers or doctors, right?

00:14:33.090 --> 00:14:34.840
They're trying to
elevate their profession

00:14:34.840 --> 00:14:39.560
and separate themselves in a
way from the work floor right?

00:14:39.560 --> 00:14:43.280
So the engineers want to
be in a glassed up area up

00:14:43.280 --> 00:14:45.170
above the factory
floor in the US, right?

00:14:45.170 --> 00:14:46.780
They don't want
to be down with--

00:14:46.780 --> 00:14:50.170
heaven forbid-- the workforce.

00:14:50.170 --> 00:14:52.540
So it's an attempt by
an engineering culture

00:14:52.540 --> 00:14:53.780
to establish its identity.

00:14:53.780 --> 00:14:55.750
You can understand
why it happened.

00:14:55.750 --> 00:14:58.853
But Japan hit on a much
better plot, right?

00:14:58.853 --> 00:15:00.520
Integrate the engineers
in the workforce

00:15:00.520 --> 00:15:02.020
and make them one, right?

00:15:02.020 --> 00:15:03.460
Much better, right?

00:15:03.460 --> 00:15:08.800
So we have learned to get
our engineers into the mix

00:15:08.800 --> 00:15:10.600
in the manufacturing sector.

00:15:10.600 --> 00:15:13.570
Japan came up with this
quality manufacturing model.

00:15:13.570 --> 00:15:16.870
Sometimes we call it here
a lean manufacturing.

00:15:16.870 --> 00:15:20.230
It led to an effort by
the US to simply copy

00:15:20.230 --> 00:15:21.430
what Japan had come up with.

00:15:21.430 --> 00:15:24.220
We had to take apart
the Toyota model.

00:15:24.220 --> 00:15:27.430
A lot of that work is
being done at MIT, right?

00:15:27.430 --> 00:15:30.790
So Dan Rus and
several others at MIT

00:15:30.790 --> 00:15:35.617
are writing up the Toyota model.

00:15:35.617 --> 00:15:37.450
And explaining it to
the rest of the country

00:15:37.450 --> 00:15:39.490
was a really important stage.

00:15:39.490 --> 00:15:42.810
Standard industry
approaches like Six Sigma

00:15:42.810 --> 00:15:45.700
that came out of
GE have essentially

00:15:45.700 --> 00:15:49.030
attempted to incorporate
Japan's quality ideas

00:15:49.030 --> 00:15:50.800
and make them pervasive
in US production

00:15:50.800 --> 00:15:53.810
for both major
manufacturers, OEM suppliers.

00:15:57.936 --> 00:16:01.760
A few other things, there's
something called the product

00:16:01.760 --> 00:16:04.340
cycle.

00:16:04.340 --> 00:16:07.040
And time is a competitive
factor in this,

00:16:07.040 --> 00:16:10.602
so eliminating time
delays and then

00:16:10.602 --> 00:16:12.560
something actually the
US really contributed to

00:16:12.560 --> 00:16:15.398
was concurrent
engineering design.

00:16:15.398 --> 00:16:16.940
So you engineers in
the room I'm sure

00:16:16.940 --> 00:16:18.107
know what I'm talking about.

00:16:18.107 --> 00:16:26.043
But in other words, if you and
I constituted Chrysler Motors,

00:16:26.043 --> 00:16:27.460
the way in which
we would organize

00:16:27.460 --> 00:16:29.992
Chrysler Motors in
the old days was

00:16:29.992 --> 00:16:31.450
we would have a
bunch of engineers,

00:16:31.450 --> 00:16:33.160
and they would do the design.

00:16:33.160 --> 00:16:35.110
And then they would
finish the design,

00:16:35.110 --> 00:16:38.350
and then they would take it
to the production people.

00:16:38.350 --> 00:16:40.140
And the production
people would say, well,

00:16:40.140 --> 00:16:42.390
that's all very well and
good, but we can't make that.

00:16:42.390 --> 00:16:44.730
So we do it, right?

00:16:44.730 --> 00:16:46.020
And then it would be redone.

00:16:46.020 --> 00:16:48.240
And then they would take it
to the engineering people

00:16:48.240 --> 00:16:52.590
again and then take it
to the marketing people.

00:16:52.590 --> 00:16:54.633
And the marketing
people would say, well,

00:16:54.633 --> 00:16:56.800
that's all very well and
good, what your engineering

00:16:56.800 --> 00:16:59.520
people have done, what your
factory floor people have done,

00:16:59.520 --> 00:17:01.320
but we can't sell this thing.

00:17:01.320 --> 00:17:03.170
So completely redo it.

00:17:03.170 --> 00:17:05.849
In other words, it was a
stage by stage process,

00:17:05.849 --> 00:17:08.060
with every stage having a veto.

00:17:08.060 --> 00:17:10.319
So the development
process for design

00:17:10.319 --> 00:17:14.550
was painful, and lengthy,
and often adversarial.

00:17:14.550 --> 00:17:17.520
Concurrent design is to put
all those teams together

00:17:17.520 --> 00:17:22.460
at the outset contributing
to the design--

00:17:22.460 --> 00:17:26.030
dramatic time savings,
dramatic efficiency savings.

00:17:26.030 --> 00:17:27.920
So these are all
kinds of ideas that

00:17:27.920 --> 00:17:30.360
came out of this time period.

00:17:30.360 --> 00:17:33.680
Another idea that Japan had--

00:17:33.680 --> 00:17:36.260
and we weren't
organized this way--

00:17:36.260 --> 00:17:43.130
Japan had a whole different
way of approaching what we

00:17:43.130 --> 00:17:47.480
could call the labor trade-off.

00:17:47.480 --> 00:17:52.900
So Japan had a system of
essentially guaranteed

00:17:52.900 --> 00:17:55.420
lifetime employment.

00:17:55.420 --> 00:17:56.800
So if you were a
worker in Japan,

00:17:56.800 --> 00:18:00.100
you were pretty well
assured in this era.

00:18:00.100 --> 00:18:05.260
It's changed a bit now, in
this era of a lifetime job.

00:18:05.260 --> 00:18:09.160
And in return for that
assurance of a lifetime job,

00:18:09.160 --> 00:18:14.080
management would control the
work rules, or what's actually

00:18:14.080 --> 00:18:17.650
happening on the factory floor,
right, now that we processed

00:18:17.650 --> 00:18:19.720
where the rule systems is.

00:18:19.720 --> 00:18:22.740
That was the trade-off.

00:18:22.740 --> 00:18:25.680
The US had a complete
different trade-off.

00:18:25.680 --> 00:18:29.850
We treated labor not as a
fixed cost, like Japan did.

00:18:29.850 --> 00:18:33.120
We treated it as
a variable cost.

00:18:33.120 --> 00:18:38.760
And the trade the unions
insisted on-- this was an era

00:18:38.760 --> 00:18:41.700
of pretty heavy unionization
of manufacturing in the US

00:18:41.700 --> 00:18:43.500
at the time--

00:18:43.500 --> 00:18:47.340
unions weren't
able to affect who

00:18:47.340 --> 00:18:50.130
gets hired and fired
in the employment

00:18:50.130 --> 00:18:51.390
side of the equation.

00:18:51.390 --> 00:18:54.690
But they would control
the workloads, right?

00:18:54.690 --> 00:18:57.470
And they designed those to
be as protective as possible

00:18:57.470 --> 00:18:59.850
as their workforces, right?

00:18:59.850 --> 00:19:02.610
Not necessarily the
most efficient system.

00:19:02.610 --> 00:19:07.680
So Japan actually had a
better model here, right?

00:19:07.680 --> 00:19:12.280
Now we continue to treat our
workforce as a variable cost,

00:19:12.280 --> 00:19:12.780
right?

00:19:12.780 --> 00:19:15.630
So whenever there's
an economic downturn,

00:19:15.630 --> 00:19:18.670
US companies dump their
workforces as a quick response,

00:19:18.670 --> 00:19:19.170
right?

00:19:19.170 --> 00:19:21.838
That's fundamental
management theory in the US.

00:19:21.838 --> 00:19:23.880
Other countries don't
necessarily do it this way.

00:19:23.880 --> 00:19:26.220
Japan has had to get more
flexible in its model

00:19:26.220 --> 00:19:30.460
as it's gone to more
global competition.

00:19:30.460 --> 00:19:32.810
But it had a completely
different way

00:19:32.810 --> 00:19:35.570
of organizing its workforce.

00:19:35.570 --> 00:19:38.690
Labor became much more
collaborative, rather than

00:19:38.690 --> 00:19:43.970
adversarial, and ready to
leap on new efficiencies

00:19:43.970 --> 00:19:46.280
in the production
process, rather than fight

00:19:46.280 --> 00:19:49.100
them every inch of the way.

00:19:49.100 --> 00:19:51.500
So again, this was a
contributing factor

00:19:51.500 --> 00:19:55.940
to the kind of new model
that Japan was creating.

00:19:55.940 --> 00:19:59.790
There's another element
here of industrial policy.

00:19:59.790 --> 00:20:03.280
So Japan is recovering
from World War II.

00:20:03.280 --> 00:20:05.060
It develops an
innovation system that

00:20:05.060 --> 00:20:08.670
is very focused on production.

00:20:08.670 --> 00:20:10.432
That's what it's got
to stand up against.

00:20:10.432 --> 00:20:12.390
And that's where this
quality model comes from,

00:20:12.390 --> 00:20:15.210
and these other pieces.

00:20:15.210 --> 00:20:19.470
And Japan is very resource poor.

00:20:19.470 --> 00:20:22.830
So starting in the
1880s, Japan understood

00:20:22.830 --> 00:20:25.440
that it had to have
an export orientation.

00:20:25.440 --> 00:20:27.930
It had to export
to live because it

00:20:27.930 --> 00:20:31.580
had to get the resources in
order to produce them, right?

00:20:31.580 --> 00:20:34.043
And buy those back, so it
needed an export surplus

00:20:34.043 --> 00:20:34.960
to be able to do that.

00:20:39.290 --> 00:20:41.840
One of its core institutions
was called MITI--

00:20:41.840 --> 00:20:46.700
Ministry of International Trade
and Industry-- now called METI.

00:20:46.700 --> 00:20:50.410
And the nickname for
this was Japan Inc.

00:20:50.410 --> 00:20:55.550
But a very integrated system
of governmental leadership

00:20:55.550 --> 00:20:56.960
tied to major industries.

00:20:56.960 --> 00:21:00.950
And the major industries
weren't organized

00:21:00.950 --> 00:21:02.840
as they were in the US.

00:21:02.840 --> 00:21:05.360
We had anti-trust
laws in the US.

00:21:05.360 --> 00:21:10.100
We did not really impose
that in the post-war period

00:21:10.100 --> 00:21:15.260
and allowed Japan to keep
its, quote, keiretsu system.

00:21:15.260 --> 00:21:20.360
So that's a system
of major firms

00:21:20.360 --> 00:21:24.470
typically engaged in production
activities, financing,

00:21:24.470 --> 00:21:27.350
global trading,
and then networks

00:21:27.350 --> 00:21:29.340
of suppliers that
are tied to those.

00:21:29.340 --> 00:21:32.810
So these are groups
of related firms

00:21:32.810 --> 00:21:35.800
that are all mutually owned and
tied to each other, all right?

00:21:35.800 --> 00:21:38.780
They would violate US anti-trust
laws in all likelihood,

00:21:38.780 --> 00:21:42.830
but that's the way Japan
organized its core industries.

00:21:42.830 --> 00:21:46.370
Now, not all Japanese firms are
part of these keiretsu, right?

00:21:46.370 --> 00:21:49.370
So a company like Sony
was actually outside

00:21:49.370 --> 00:21:51.200
of this, right?

00:21:51.200 --> 00:21:53.210
But most of its
industry was organized

00:21:53.210 --> 00:21:54.710
in this very simple kind of way.

00:21:54.710 --> 00:21:56.270
And you can see
how their dealings

00:21:56.270 --> 00:21:57.860
with a major
governmental entity,

00:21:57.860 --> 00:22:03.890
like MITI, could be readily tied
to unify government decision

00:22:03.890 --> 00:22:07.680
making and industry
decision making.

00:22:07.680 --> 00:22:11.840
So when the US was
competing against Japan

00:22:11.840 --> 00:22:16.810
in this quite centralized,
quite efficient model,

00:22:16.810 --> 00:22:19.040
US had a lot of trouble coping.

00:22:19.040 --> 00:22:22.960
And you've seen them--

00:22:22.960 --> 00:22:24.430
when we talked
about Jorgenson, you

00:22:24.430 --> 00:22:30.070
saw some of the
productivity and GDP curbs.

00:22:30.070 --> 00:22:37.270
So historic US
productivity rate generally

00:22:37.270 --> 00:22:41.390
around 2%, and historic US GDP
growth is generally around 3%,

00:22:41.390 --> 00:22:44.170
right?

00:22:44.170 --> 00:22:49.540
Between '73 and
'91, those plummet,

00:22:49.540 --> 00:22:53.260
so we fall to productivity
rates at around 1%

00:22:53.260 --> 00:22:55.420
and GDP growth about 2%.

00:22:55.420 --> 00:22:58.810
It was a pretty grim time
in the United States.

00:22:58.810 --> 00:23:01.780
We were up against a powerful
industrial competitor,

00:23:01.780 --> 00:23:06.910
and Japan was able to
take economic sectors

00:23:06.910 --> 00:23:08.860
that the US thought
it would always have,

00:23:08.860 --> 00:23:11.650
like consumer electronics,
like a large part of the auto

00:23:11.650 --> 00:23:12.250
sector.

00:23:12.250 --> 00:23:14.050
Because it had a better
innovation model.

00:23:19.160 --> 00:23:25.460
So in a very brief
period of time,

00:23:25.460 --> 00:23:29.310
that's kind of what
happened in the 70s and 80s.

00:23:29.310 --> 00:23:32.270
The US response, as
I suggested earlier,

00:23:32.270 --> 00:23:36.590
was that we would attempt
to copy Japan on quality.

00:23:36.590 --> 00:23:38.540
And we call it
lean manufacturing,

00:23:38.540 --> 00:23:42.740
but we would attempt to
replicate as much as we could

00:23:42.740 --> 00:23:45.020
of that Toyota model.

00:23:45.020 --> 00:23:50.780
And by and large, our industries
have pretty well done that.

00:23:50.780 --> 00:23:56.570
But we also kept a focus on our
very strong innovation system.

00:23:56.570 --> 00:24:04.540
So we launched in the 1990s
the IT innovation wave,

00:24:04.540 --> 00:24:09.700
which Japan misses, right?

00:24:09.700 --> 00:24:13.910
And if you get your economy
to a leadership right

00:24:13.910 --> 00:24:16.650
to the edge of the
technological frontier,

00:24:16.650 --> 00:24:19.100
and you organize your economy
around leading innovation

00:24:19.100 --> 00:24:21.260
ways with Japan and just
organize its economy

00:24:21.260 --> 00:24:23.900
around doing, around a
new production system,

00:24:23.900 --> 00:24:27.080
and then you miss a wave,
it can be pretty unpleasant,

00:24:27.080 --> 00:24:27.630
all right?

00:24:27.630 --> 00:24:29.930
So it was unpleasant in the
US when we missed a wave

00:24:29.930 --> 00:24:31.550
in the '70s and '80s.

00:24:31.550 --> 00:24:33.282
But then things got
tough for Japan.

00:24:33.282 --> 00:24:35.240
Now that's not the only
factor that's going on.

00:24:35.240 --> 00:24:38.310
There's macroeconomic factors.

00:24:38.310 --> 00:24:39.910
There's demographic factors.

00:24:39.910 --> 00:24:42.410
There's a series of things that
are occurring simultaneously

00:24:42.410 --> 00:24:43.035
in Japan.

00:24:43.035 --> 00:24:46.032
But one part of
the story is around

00:24:46.032 --> 00:24:47.240
missing this innovation wave.

00:24:47.240 --> 00:24:51.400
So that was the kind of response
that the US came up with.

00:24:54.100 --> 00:24:57.730
It used its innovation
system to develop effectively

00:24:57.730 --> 00:25:00.370
radical innovations
in the IT space

00:25:00.370 --> 00:25:02.720
and create whole new industries.

00:25:02.720 --> 00:25:05.830
So we pursue radical innovation.

00:25:08.620 --> 00:25:10.240
Not consciously--
but in a way, that

00:25:10.240 --> 00:25:13.720
was effectively our response.

