00:32:08.270 --> 00:32:09.478
to kind of do the same thing?

00:32:11.880 --> 00:32:15.140
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: I mean, just
a comment from my background

00:32:15.140 --> 00:32:18.990
experience having worked in
the Senate for about 15 years--

00:32:18.990 --> 00:32:23.400
yes, the committees
of Congress can

00:32:23.400 --> 00:32:27.050
function on an ongoing
basis to try and identify,

00:32:27.050 --> 00:32:29.290
Kevin, exactly the
problem you were raising,

00:32:29.290 --> 00:32:31.088
which is be a
little foresighted.

00:32:31.088 --> 00:32:33.630
Some committees are obviously
much better at this than others

00:32:33.630 --> 00:32:34.770
historically.

00:32:37.960 --> 00:32:39.620
But there's no guarantees.

00:32:39.620 --> 00:32:44.180
And frankly, government
tends to respond to crises.

00:32:44.180 --> 00:32:46.630
And if there's
not a crisis, it's

00:32:46.630 --> 00:32:48.320
hard to get it
mobilized, organizing,

00:32:48.320 --> 00:32:51.100
and moving to be foresighted.

00:32:51.100 --> 00:32:53.750
That's not necessarily
all bad, right?

00:32:53.750 --> 00:32:57.670
There's advantages
of having limits

00:32:57.670 --> 00:33:01.090
on governmental
intervention here.

00:33:01.090 --> 00:33:03.800
And if the system is
working fairly well,

00:33:03.800 --> 00:33:06.600
you probably don't want
government intervention.

00:33:06.600 --> 00:33:09.100
It's only when you hit a
crisis moment that you really

00:33:09.100 --> 00:33:11.890
want it to fall into place.

00:33:11.890 --> 00:33:14.042
I understand,
though, your points

00:33:14.042 --> 00:33:16.000
about wouldn't it be
better if we were watching

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:17.167
all this stuff all the time.

00:33:17.167 --> 00:33:18.940
So there is that reality.

00:33:18.940 --> 00:33:23.860
You've got to hope that somebody
somewhere in the society

00:33:23.860 --> 00:33:25.840
is undertaking that review.

00:33:25.840 --> 00:33:28.268
But it's not something
government is terribly good at.

00:33:31.550 --> 00:33:34.550
And a typical response to a
crisis in a short term kind

00:33:34.550 --> 00:33:35.160
of way.

00:33:35.160 --> 00:33:38.150
So we came up with these
various mechanisms,

00:33:38.150 --> 00:33:40.780
none could really be called
a competitiveness strategy.

00:33:40.780 --> 00:33:43.430
We came up with a
bunch of pieces, right?

00:33:43.430 --> 00:33:46.550
One piece that's not
on here was Symantec,

00:33:46.550 --> 00:33:52.370
which is an attempt to
deal with Japan's effort

00:33:52.370 --> 00:33:55.640
to really capture the
semiconductor sector, which,

00:33:55.640 --> 00:33:57.890
again, produced very
high quality production

00:33:57.890 --> 00:34:02.250
capabilities and in
semiconductor chips,

00:34:02.250 --> 00:34:03.380
particularly DRAMs.

00:34:03.380 --> 00:34:07.940
And the US was producing
a lot of chips,

00:34:07.940 --> 00:34:10.550
but they were not
as high quality.

00:34:10.550 --> 00:34:13.610
And the manufacturing
process was not as efficient

00:34:13.610 --> 00:34:15.050
as Japan was.

00:34:15.050 --> 00:34:18.130
So Canon and Nikon
were opposed to be

00:34:18.130 --> 00:34:21.110
able to capture a very
large part of that sector.

00:34:21.110 --> 00:34:23.090
The solution the
US came up with--

00:34:23.090 --> 00:34:24.409
and again, this is DoD--

00:34:24.409 --> 00:34:26.690
the Department of Defense--

00:34:26.690 --> 00:34:29.210
which viewed semiconductors
as a pretty critical

00:34:29.210 --> 00:34:31.587
national security technology.

00:34:31.587 --> 00:34:33.920
Because it was embedded in
all kinds of critical defense

00:34:33.920 --> 00:34:36.100
technologies.

00:34:36.100 --> 00:34:40.219
DoD agreed to cost share
with the big industry

00:34:40.219 --> 00:34:45.530
organization consisting of both
the semiconductor fabricators,

00:34:45.530 --> 00:34:49.730
but also the supplier system,
the equipment and parts

00:34:49.730 --> 00:34:51.949
suppliers system for
the semiconductor

00:34:51.949 --> 00:34:53.830
in this community.

00:34:53.830 --> 00:34:56.350
That community came
together, eventually settled

00:34:56.350 --> 00:34:59.230
on a series of steps
to build quality

00:34:59.230 --> 00:35:03.870
into the US semiconductor
manufacturing process.

00:35:03.870 --> 00:35:09.083
Cost shared with DARPA, and it
really turned around a sector.

00:35:09.083 --> 00:35:11.250
Now there are other
developments going on here, too.

00:35:11.250 --> 00:35:15.180
The US taking leadership
of integrated circuits

00:35:15.180 --> 00:35:18.660
and microprocessors, kind of
the next stage of technology,

00:35:18.660 --> 00:35:21.450
so that certainly helped.

00:35:21.450 --> 00:35:23.640
But nonetheless, the
effort to drive quality

00:35:23.640 --> 00:35:28.830
into semiconductor production
was a very concrete example

00:35:28.830 --> 00:35:33.180
of an industry and
governmental collaboration

00:35:33.180 --> 00:35:35.310
that actually worked.

00:35:35.310 --> 00:35:37.720
So these other pieces here
are a little more hands-off--

00:35:37.720 --> 00:35:42.170
CRETA, Bayh-Dole Act, the
Advanced Technology Program,

00:35:42.170 --> 00:35:43.170
but not as direct.

00:35:43.170 --> 00:35:45.055
Symantec was a
fairly direct effort

00:35:45.055 --> 00:35:46.430
in the particular
economic sector

00:35:46.430 --> 00:35:50.120
with national security
ramifications to intervene.

00:35:50.120 --> 00:35:53.070
So in some ways, that's
the most seminal model that

00:35:53.070 --> 00:35:55.020
came out of this time period.

00:35:55.020 --> 00:35:58.830
But again, the minute
that the IT revolution

00:35:58.830 --> 00:36:03.810
starts to take off at the
beginning of the '90s, then

00:36:03.810 --> 00:36:07.350
the US drops its concern
with manufacturing, right?

00:36:07.350 --> 00:36:12.600
And we go on to having a great
time for a decade with the IT

00:36:12.600 --> 00:36:15.540
revolution, which,
as we discussed,

00:36:15.540 --> 00:36:19.698
is a remarkable period of growth
and of economic well-being

00:36:19.698 --> 00:36:20.198
in the US.

00:36:23.340 --> 00:36:25.310
How about another one, RASHEED?

00:36:25.310 --> 00:36:26.190
RASHEED: For Hughes?

00:36:26.190 --> 00:36:31.830
Yeah, I think we kind
of center our discussion

00:36:31.830 --> 00:36:35.890
a little bit on the US response
to what's going on in Japan.

00:36:35.890 --> 00:36:38.460
But I thought it might be
interesting to at least touch

00:36:38.460 --> 00:36:42.370
on how the different
paradigms-- and so

00:36:42.370 --> 00:36:43.600
the US and Japanese culture.

00:36:43.600 --> 00:36:49.358
So in Japan, we've talked about
kind of like these workers

00:36:49.358 --> 00:36:50.650
treating labor as a big source.

00:36:50.650 --> 00:36:52.950
And so you're sort
of employed for life.

00:36:52.950 --> 00:36:54.390
These paradigms
play out in Japan,

00:36:54.390 --> 00:36:56.880
and they're just kind of
characteristics of the culture.

00:36:56.880 --> 00:37:00.487
But I think looking at
international trade,

00:37:00.487 --> 00:37:02.070
is this sort of the
first time that we

00:37:02.070 --> 00:37:05.760
had to deal with a
difference in paradigm

00:37:05.760 --> 00:37:09.113
affecting international
trade, and basically just

00:37:09.113 --> 00:37:10.530
the fundamentals
of the US economy

00:37:10.530 --> 00:37:14.592
in a pretty large
and widespread way?

00:37:14.592 --> 00:37:16.050
Because I guess,
globalization will

00:37:16.050 --> 00:37:18.248
bring new countries
and new actors

00:37:18.248 --> 00:37:19.290
acting in different ways.

00:37:19.290 --> 00:37:22.950
But there's sort
of no competition

00:37:22.950 --> 00:37:26.880
until Japan sort of poses
this entirely different model

00:37:26.880 --> 00:37:28.570
for how to do things.

00:37:28.570 --> 00:37:33.000
But I'd like to at least touch
on how does kind of setting up

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:35.160
your problem and your
paradigms in this way,

00:37:35.160 --> 00:37:39.730
does that provide opportunity
for sort of new innovation

00:37:39.730 --> 00:37:46.050
ways, in that if I set up
postwar Japan in a slightly

00:37:46.050 --> 00:37:49.260
different way, do I get a
slightly different outcome?

00:37:49.260 --> 00:37:50.550
STUDENT 4: I was wondering--

00:37:50.550 --> 00:37:52.620
this might help answer that--

00:37:52.620 --> 00:37:57.960
does Japan have the equivalent
of the US labor union?

00:38:00.190 --> 00:38:01.940
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
Yeah, the labor unions

00:38:01.940 --> 00:38:04.610
are organized very
differently however--

00:38:04.610 --> 00:38:06.740
far less adversarial.

00:38:06.740 --> 00:38:09.500
Again, if you have a lifetime
guarantee of work what's

00:38:09.500 --> 00:38:11.950
there to fight about, right?

00:38:11.950 --> 00:38:14.060
Why do you want to
have fights, right?

00:38:14.060 --> 00:38:16.610
Instead, they're much more
collaborative institutions

00:38:16.610 --> 00:38:21.170
that tend towards moving
towards great efficiency

00:38:21.170 --> 00:38:26.030
to promote their
company's performance.

00:38:26.030 --> 00:38:30.665
There's much greater incentive
for collaboration in the system

00:38:30.665 --> 00:38:32.450
that they set up.

00:38:32.450 --> 00:38:37.400
Now again, some of
that is faded as Japan

00:38:37.400 --> 00:38:41.930
has entered a much more
globalized competitive world

00:38:41.930 --> 00:38:48.110
of competition than it faced
as its system was emerging.

00:38:48.110 --> 00:38:57.860
But the trade-off of getting
cooperation from labor

00:38:57.860 --> 00:39:02.100
around work rules in return
for a lifetime employment

00:39:02.100 --> 00:39:06.170
has tended to work
well for Japan.

00:39:06.170 --> 00:39:08.640
In fact, the US auto
industry was actually

00:39:08.640 --> 00:39:17.410
moving in that direction for
a time period before, again,

00:39:17.410 --> 00:39:20.320
high competition kind
of caught up with it.

00:39:20.320 --> 00:39:23.080
But it's just that labor
trade-off is just a completely

00:39:23.080 --> 00:39:24.266
different arrangement.

00:39:26.930 --> 00:39:30.870
Look, I don't want to
underestimate these big macro

00:39:30.870 --> 00:39:32.670
factors that are
playing here, right?

00:39:32.670 --> 00:39:37.340
So at the end of the
World War II era, the US

00:39:37.340 --> 00:39:40.245
and the developed world--

00:39:43.470 --> 00:39:44.850
non-Communist
world-- essentially

00:39:44.850 --> 00:39:51.150
came to a set of arrangements
around free trade concepts,

00:39:51.150 --> 00:39:58.610
and open economies, and lowering
tariff and trade barriers

00:39:58.610 --> 00:39:59.180
and so forth.

00:39:59.180 --> 00:40:03.025
And that was the consensus
system of the time.

00:40:05.770 --> 00:40:09.220
When Japan organized its
economy and really began

00:40:09.220 --> 00:40:14.330
to move on entry as a
global economic power,

00:40:14.330 --> 00:40:16.510
it organized around a
different set of concepts.

00:40:16.510 --> 00:40:19.150
It was not organized around
a free trading system.

00:40:19.150 --> 00:40:22.210
It was organized around a
pretty mercantilist approach.

00:40:22.210 --> 00:40:25.300
Again, as part of
Japan's history,

00:40:25.300 --> 00:40:28.240
it has to trade to survive.

00:40:28.240 --> 00:40:30.820
It has to export
to survive, right?

00:40:30.820 --> 00:40:36.490
So they developed a very
focused export system.

00:40:36.490 --> 00:40:42.710
They undervalue their currency
so that their manufacturers

00:40:42.710 --> 00:40:45.020
would always have a
price advantage over US

00:40:45.020 --> 00:40:46.460
manufacturers, right?

00:40:46.460 --> 00:40:49.340
US put up with that
for essentially world

00:40:49.340 --> 00:40:52.980
national security kind
of reasons with an ally.

00:40:52.980 --> 00:40:55.730
And we assumed we were
kings of manufacturing.

00:40:55.730 --> 00:40:59.120
Who could interfere with us?

00:40:59.120 --> 00:41:01.610
Japan had a much more
interventionist attitude

00:41:01.610 --> 00:41:03.650
by its government into
supporting particular

00:41:03.650 --> 00:41:05.780
and assisting particular firms.

00:41:05.780 --> 00:41:09.650
That was not like the US system.

00:41:09.650 --> 00:41:12.710
It made it very
hard for imports,

00:41:12.710 --> 00:41:15.110
particularly of
complex technologies,

00:41:15.110 --> 00:41:18.020
to enter the Japanese markets.

00:41:18.020 --> 00:41:20.840
So it was playing by a different
set of more mercantilist

00:41:20.840 --> 00:41:22.280
kinds of rules.

00:41:22.280 --> 00:41:24.620
And frankly, that
model became a model

00:41:24.620 --> 00:41:26.130
for other Asian economies.

00:41:26.130 --> 00:41:30.800
So that was a model that worked
for Taiwan, and for Korea,

00:41:30.800 --> 00:41:32.280
and now China.

00:41:32.280 --> 00:41:36.545
And it's not based on that open
trading regime consensus policy

00:41:36.545 --> 00:41:39.660
that the US tried to build
at the end of World War II.

00:41:39.660 --> 00:41:42.050
So we're up against different
economic models here.

00:41:42.050 --> 00:41:45.140
Part of the story is that
the US hasn't really figured

00:41:45.140 --> 00:41:46.730
out what the right strategy is.

