00:48:50.040 --> 00:48:55.110
So Barry Lynn argues
that there's essentially

00:48:55.110 --> 00:48:59.968
three periods of
US manufacturing

00:48:59.968 --> 00:49:00.760
industrial history.

00:49:05.570 --> 00:49:10.570
There is a period between
Alexander Hamilton.

00:49:10.570 --> 00:49:15.290
And we call it 1945, the
end of World War II, right?

00:49:15.290 --> 00:49:20.120
And I mean, Hamilton is a
absolutely critical figure

00:49:20.120 --> 00:49:28.700
in US economic history because
he had a remarkably big picture

00:49:28.700 --> 00:49:31.790
of what the US
economy could become,

00:49:31.790 --> 00:49:35.322
a bigger picture than
anybody of this time

00:49:35.322 --> 00:49:37.680
in the political system.

00:49:37.680 --> 00:49:40.980
So and his fundamental
understanding

00:49:40.980 --> 00:49:49.330
was that in this era of
a small new power faced

00:49:49.330 --> 00:49:54.190
with much larger contending
European nations,

00:49:54.190 --> 00:49:58.570
that the only way that the
US keeps its independence

00:49:58.570 --> 00:50:01.928
is by building a strong
independent commercial economy,

00:50:01.928 --> 00:50:03.680
right?

00:50:03.680 --> 00:50:05.590
So Thomas Jefferson
at the same time

00:50:05.590 --> 00:50:08.510
is devoted to an
agricultural economy

00:50:08.510 --> 00:50:10.440
and a concept of young farmer.

00:50:10.440 --> 00:50:13.610
And that's how democracy
is going to take place.

00:50:13.610 --> 00:50:15.960
Hamilton is working in a
completely different direction.

00:50:15.960 --> 00:50:19.400
Let's stand up a major
national banking system.

00:50:19.400 --> 00:50:21.320
Let's stand up a major
commercial economy.

00:50:21.320 --> 00:50:27.440
And he himself is strongly
dedicated to early US

00:50:27.440 --> 00:50:28.490
manufacturing industry.

00:50:28.490 --> 00:50:33.466
So he's investing in an early
manufacturing plant across New

00:50:33.466 --> 00:50:36.410
York City and in New Jersey.

00:50:36.410 --> 00:50:39.980
So Hamilton's
concept was that we

00:50:39.980 --> 00:50:44.780
need to pursue
rational national self

00:50:44.780 --> 00:50:46.910
dependence in manufacturing.

00:50:46.910 --> 00:50:48.920
And tariffs are
fine because that

00:50:48.920 --> 00:50:52.580
will ensure the growth of US
manufacturing and production

00:50:52.580 --> 00:50:55.340
capability in the US economy.

00:50:55.340 --> 00:50:59.410
And he creates a lot of the
fundamental institutions

00:50:59.410 --> 00:51:03.660
that frankly, we still rely
on in maintaining that very

00:51:03.660 --> 00:51:06.190
small commercial economy.

00:51:06.190 --> 00:51:12.850
Then there is the post-World War
II emergence of the Cold War.

00:51:12.850 --> 00:51:17.380
And Lynn argues that
the US government

00:51:17.380 --> 00:51:21.820
leaves its Hamiltonian
notions of national self

00:51:21.820 --> 00:51:27.850
dependence in manufacturing to
build a larger concept, right?

00:51:27.850 --> 00:51:29.860
Confronted with an
international confrontation

00:51:29.860 --> 00:51:32.910
with a different
economic system,

00:51:32.910 --> 00:51:38.890
the US works towards building
a world economy that integrates

00:51:38.890 --> 00:51:41.322
the US, Europe, and
Japan in particular,

00:51:41.322 --> 00:51:42.280
and other nations, too.

00:51:42.280 --> 00:51:44.670
But those are the
principal ones--

00:51:44.670 --> 00:51:48.400
in a system of mutual
dependence, right?

00:51:48.400 --> 00:51:53.520
So this is not a self
dependent manufacturing system.

00:51:53.520 --> 00:51:55.620
This starts to move
us in the direction

00:51:55.620 --> 00:51:59.580
of a multi-continent
production system that's

00:51:59.580 --> 00:52:03.160
going to be shared
by the participants.

00:52:03.160 --> 00:52:06.180
And then Lynn argues that
the third stage really

00:52:06.180 --> 00:52:15.540
occurs in the 1990s as President
Clinton moves to move China

00:52:15.540 --> 00:52:18.210
into the world economic system.

00:52:18.210 --> 00:52:21.810
And that notion there is a--

00:52:24.440 --> 00:52:27.230
it's a similar notion
to what occurs in Europe

00:52:27.230 --> 00:52:29.000
in the post-war period.

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:30.680
That if they integrate
their economies

00:52:30.680 --> 00:52:32.180
and they all own
each other, they're

00:52:32.180 --> 00:52:34.260
never going to fight
World War II again.

00:52:34.260 --> 00:52:35.480
All right?

00:52:35.480 --> 00:52:38.630
There's a lot to be said
for that concept, frankly.

00:52:38.630 --> 00:52:44.960
That an economically
interdependent integrated world

00:52:44.960 --> 00:52:48.050
is going to significantly
reduce national security threats

00:52:48.050 --> 00:52:48.710
over time.

00:52:48.710 --> 00:52:51.920
That's essentially,
Barry Lynn argues,

00:52:51.920 --> 00:52:56.220
Clinton's driving
conceptual framework

00:52:56.220 --> 00:52:58.560
that this interdependent
economic system, tied

00:52:58.560 --> 00:53:01.830
by joint manufacturing
and a common set

00:53:01.830 --> 00:53:06.540
of economic organizations,
will enable world peace, right?

00:53:06.540 --> 00:53:08.130
That's the notion.

00:53:08.130 --> 00:53:12.900
So the WTO agreement and
China's entry into the WTO

00:53:12.900 --> 00:53:16.770
is the critical
enabling step here.

00:53:16.770 --> 00:53:21.480
And the west production
system is indeed,

00:53:21.480 --> 00:53:24.930
to a significant extent,
merged into China

00:53:24.930 --> 00:53:29.130
with China's production
output going worldwide.

00:53:29.130 --> 00:53:32.400
Now there's a whole defense set
of perspectives here, right?

00:53:32.400 --> 00:53:36.570
There are integrationists,
which Clinton would be one,

00:53:36.570 --> 00:53:40.900
