01:06:29.885 --> 01:06:32.260
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: So let me
put this in a different way

01:06:32.260 --> 01:06:32.760
here.

01:06:36.400 --> 01:06:38.200
We've been targeting
an innovation wave.

01:06:38.200 --> 01:06:41.230
I think this
significant argument

01:06:41.230 --> 01:06:46.870
that the explosion of
the financial services

01:06:46.870 --> 01:06:53.900
sector, incredibly rapid growth
in financial services sector,

01:06:53.900 --> 01:06:58.170
in the 1990s, in the 2000s,
that's an innovation wave.

01:06:58.170 --> 01:07:00.870
There certainly were
technological innovations

01:07:00.870 --> 01:07:02.250
that were at the heart of this.

01:07:02.250 --> 01:07:05.940
The IT revolution was clearly
a great organizing factor.

01:07:05.940 --> 01:07:09.080
The ability to bring
mathematics to bear,

01:07:09.080 --> 01:07:14.010
to work on a problem of big data
and initial kinds of analytics

01:07:14.010 --> 01:07:16.830
to bring algorithms to
bear on market trading--

01:07:16.830 --> 01:07:20.070
these were all significant
technology advances

01:07:20.070 --> 01:07:27.940
that were enablers of creating
a truly globalized system.

01:07:27.940 --> 01:07:30.220
And we moved at a
relatively short period

01:07:30.220 --> 01:07:35.810
from national systems, financial
services and financial service

01:07:35.810 --> 01:07:38.120
organizations to much
larger global systems.

01:07:38.120 --> 01:07:41.330
So when the US
economy went down,

01:07:41.330 --> 01:07:44.000
it hit the rest of
the world economy.

01:07:44.000 --> 01:07:45.920
US financial system went down.

01:07:45.920 --> 01:07:49.250
It hit the rest of the
world economy in wave

01:07:49.250 --> 01:07:51.380
after wave after wave
and began to jeopardize

01:07:51.380 --> 01:07:54.320
a whole nest of other
financial institutions

01:07:54.320 --> 01:07:57.800
that were caught up in this
very integrated kind of system.

01:07:57.800 --> 01:08:01.640
So that's more of what
I'm driving at, Max.

01:08:01.640 --> 01:08:06.140
And look, as we've discussed
in innovation waves,

01:08:06.140 --> 01:08:08.330
there's always a bubble, right?

01:08:08.330 --> 01:08:10.800
And the problem
with having a bubble

01:08:10.800 --> 01:08:13.250
in your financial
services sector

01:08:13.250 --> 01:08:14.990
is that it brings
down everything.

01:08:14.990 --> 01:08:17.490
It's one thing to have
a bubble with dot coms.

01:08:17.490 --> 01:08:20.300
Yeah, lose the dot
coms, but if you

01:08:20.300 --> 01:08:23.029
lose the world
financial system because

01:08:23.029 --> 01:08:27.290
of the technological bubble,
it's pretty powerful.

01:08:27.290 --> 01:08:29.500
Andrew Lowe is a wonderful
professor of finance

01:08:29.500 --> 01:08:31.670
here at MIT.

01:08:31.670 --> 01:08:33.620
Has a remarkable chart, right?

01:08:33.620 --> 01:08:37.970
The chart is-- it's the
history of the value

01:08:37.970 --> 01:08:43.100
of home prices adjusted for
inflation in the United States.

01:08:43.100 --> 01:08:44.779
And it's a hockey stick.

01:08:44.779 --> 01:08:48.680
OK, so it's inflation adjusted.

01:08:48.680 --> 01:08:50.750
It's flat, and the
numbers start getting put

01:08:50.750 --> 01:08:52.100
together in about the 1880s.

01:08:52.100 --> 01:08:54.800
And should you go on the 1880s,
there's the Great Depression,

01:08:54.800 --> 01:08:55.300
right?

01:08:55.300 --> 01:08:58.000
A couple of recessions,
but it's pretty stable.

01:08:58.000 --> 01:09:01.330
Then about 1990, it
just skyrockets, right?

01:09:01.330 --> 01:09:05.120
It just skyrockets, and you
wonder what were we thinking?

01:09:05.120 --> 01:09:07.520
I mean, this is clearly
going to be a bubble.

01:09:07.520 --> 01:09:10.580
Why was it that the financial
services sector decided

01:09:10.580 --> 01:09:14.450
that the ultimate fundamental
unit of value in the world

01:09:14.450 --> 01:09:16.910
financial order is going to
be the American home mortgage?

01:09:16.910 --> 01:09:18.529
Why did we do this, right?

01:09:18.529 --> 01:09:19.609
What were we thinking?

01:09:19.609 --> 01:09:22.729
But in a way, that's
exactly what we do.

01:09:22.729 --> 01:09:24.560
Now, Andrew goes on
to make an argument.

01:09:24.560 --> 01:09:29.630
We developed all these very
interesting new financial tools

01:09:29.630 --> 01:09:31.340
in the course of
that innovation wave.

01:09:31.340 --> 01:09:33.465
He wouldn't necessarily
call it an innovation wave,

01:09:33.465 --> 01:09:35.359
but I would.

01:09:35.359 --> 01:09:37.970
Let's figure out
if we can settle

01:09:37.970 --> 01:09:42.200
on some better units of
value than the American home

